Optional, and streams together.

Null is famously called the billion-dollar mistake. It is a value that type-checks as any reference type, but crashes your program the instant you dereference it. Java still has null, but for a return value that might legitimately be absent, the modern signature is optional of T. An optional is a small wrapper that either holds a value or is empty, and it forces you to acknowledge the empty case before you can reach the value inside.

You create one with optional dot of, which throws if you hand it null, or optional dot of-nullable, which quietly turns a null into an empty optional. Then you read it safely. If-present runs an action only when a value is there. Or-else gives you a fallback value. Or-else-get takes a supplier and computes the fallback lazily, only if needed. Or-else-throw raises an exception you choose when it is empty. And map lets you transform the value while it stays inside the wrapper. The one method to avoid is a bare get with no check, which just reintroduces the null-pointer problem under a new name.

There is one firm convention: use optional as a return type only. Do not use it for fields, for method parameters, or for elements of a collection; there, a sensible default or an empty collection is better. Finally, optional and streams were designed to compose. The stream operations that might find nothing, like find-first, min, and max, all return an optional, so you can filter a stream, find the first match, map it to something, and fall back with or-else, all in one clean chain.
